Record the type and stack of every allocation (or only at a given sample interval), and print to an output stream as JSON.

Alternate approach to existing alloc profiler PR: https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/pull/33467
Complementary to garbage profiler PR: https://github.com/JuliaLang/julia/pull/42658 (maybe there's some nice way to meld them)

This may be reinventing the wheel from #33467, but I'm not sure why that one needs stuff like LLVM passes. I mimicked some stuff from it, but this was my attempt to get something up and running. Could easily be missing stuff.

## Usage:

```julia
using AllocProfile

res, profile = AllocProfile.@profile 100_000 begin
  # code you wanna profile
end
# do something with `profile`
```

## Output:

Julia structs which can be used by downstream libraries. (See `AllocProfile.jl`)

## Analysis

Can use https://github.com/vilterp/AllocProfileParser.jl to rehydrate the files and work with them a bit more easily in Julia. Maybe that library could be used to munge the data into FlameGraphs / PProf.

