This works when the backtrace entries are pointers to generated code, but not when they're interpreter frames, since those frames have a more complicated encoding, and point to objects on the heap. The function `reformat_bt` in `errors.jl` can handle decoding, but it doesn't work well in a profiling setting, because the interpreter frame objects pointed to the backtrace entries can be garbage collected while the profiler is still running, before it has a chance to decode them!

In another memory profiling PR, @maleadt solved this problem by modifying the garbage collector's mark phase to find these pointers in backtrace buffers, thereby preventing them from being collected. Perhaps that change can be merged separately, so then both the allocation and CPU profilers can use `reformat_bt`, and include interpreter frames.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/43796/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"timeline_url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/43796/timeline","performed_via_github_app":null}}

